{"action":"write_file","file_content":"# useEffect Antipatterns in Next.js Client Components

Common mistakes when using `useEffect` that cause bugs, infinite loops, or silent failures.

## Silent Failures (Most Common)

### Pattern: Promise Rejection Without Handler

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const fetchProducts = async () => {
    const { data, error } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
    // If this errors, nothing happens - console silent
    setProducts(data)
  }
  fetchProducts()
}, [])
```

**Problem:**
- If Supabase query fails, promise rejects silently
- `setProducts` might not fire, or `setLoading(false)` never called
- User sees infinite loading skeleton

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  ;(async () => {
    try {
      const { data, error } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
      if (error) {
        console.error("Failed to fetch products:", error)
        // Optionally: setError(error.message)
      } else if (data) {
        setProducts(data)
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("Exception in fetch:", err)
    } finally {
      setLoading(false)  // ALWAYS runs, even on error
    }
  })()
}, [])
```

**Key rule:** Wrap async operations in try-catch and use `finally` for cleanup/state setters.

## Infinite Loops

### Pattern: Dependency Array Issue

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const { data } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
  setProducts(data)
}, [products])  // ❌ products changes → effect runs → products changes → infinite loop
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const { data } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
  setProducts(data)
}, [])  // ✅ Run once on mount
```

### Pattern: Object Reference Dependency

**Bad:**
```tsx
const supabase = createClient()  // New object on every render

useEffect(() => {
  // Runs every render because supabase reference changes
}, [supabase])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
// Move outside component or memoize
import { createClient } from "@/lib/supabase/client"

export default function Component() {
  const supabase = useMemo(() => createClient(), [])

  useEffect(() => {
    // Runs once
  }, [supabase])
}
```

## Memory Leaks

### Pattern: Not Cleaning Up Subscriptions

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const channel = supabase.channel('changes').on('postgres_changes', ...).subscribe()
  // ❌ Never unsubscribes - leaks on unmount
}, [])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const channel = supabase.channel('changes').on('postgres_changes', ...).subscribe()

  return () => {
    supabase.removeChannel(channel)  // ✅ Cleanup on unmount
  }
}, [])
```

### Pattern: Aborting Fetch on Unmount

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch('/api/products')
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setData(data))
  // ❌ If component unmounts, this still tries to setData
}, [])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController()

  fetch('/api/products', { signal: controller.signal })
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setData(data))
    .catch(err => {
      if (err.name !== 'AbortError') {
        console.error(err)
      }
    })

  return () => controller.abort()  // ✅ Cancel on unmount
}, [])
```

## Race Conditions

### Pattern: Old Data Overwriting New

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  // If user changes route quickly, both requests fire
  // Second request finishes first, then first request overwrites
  fetchProduct(id).then(setProduct)
}, [id])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  let isMounted = true

  fetchProduct(id).then(data => {
    if (isMounted) {
      setProduct(data)  // Only set if component still mounted
    }
  })

  return () => { isMounted = false }
}, [id])
```

## State Initialization Timing

### Pattern: Derived State in useEffect

**Bad:**
```tsx
const [products, setProducts] = useState([])
const [featured, setFeatured] = useState([])

useEffect(() => {
  setFeatured(products.filter(p => p.featured))  // Runs after render
}, [products])
```

**Better:** Derive directly, no useEffect needed
```tsx
const [products, setProducts] = useState([])
const featured = products.filter(p => p.featured)  // ✅ Instant, no lag
```

### Pattern: Not Handling Empty State

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const { data } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
  // data might be null or []
  data.forEach(p => ...)  // ❌ Crash if data is null
}, [])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const { data } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
  if (data && data.length > 0) {
    data.forEach(p => ...)
  }
}, [])
```

## Async/Await Gotchas

### Pattern: Not Using IIFE

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const fetch = async () => { ... }
  fetch()  // ❌ If useEffect callback returns promise, React warns
}, [])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  ;(async () => {
    // ✅ IIFE pattern
    const data = await fetchSomething()
  })()
}, [])
```

### Pattern: Async Function as Effect Callback

**Bad:**
```tsx
useEffect(async () => {  // ❌ Can't make effect callback async
  const data = await fetchSomething()
  setData(data)
}, [])
```

**Good:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const fetchData = async () => {
    const data = await fetchSomething()
    setData(data)
  }
  fetchData()
}, [])
```

## Checklist Before Committing useEffect Code

- [ ] Wrapped in try-catch
- [ ] `finally` block sets loading to false
- [ ] Dependency array is correct (no infinite loops)
- [ ] Cleanup function returns (subscriptions, abort controllers)
- [ ] Not directly async effect callback (use IIFE or named function)
- [ ] Check for null/undefined before array methods
- [ ] No derived state in useEffect (compute directly instead)

## Debug Pattern: Add Logging

When in doubt, log everything:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  console.log("Effect running with deps:", { id, slug })

  const fetchData = async () => {
    console.log("Starting fetch...")
    try {
      const { data, error } = await supabase.from("products").select("*")
      console.log("Fetch result:", { 
        count: data?.length, 
        error: error?.message 
      })
      setProducts(data)
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("Fetch exception:", err)
    } finally {
      console.log("Fetch complete, setting loaded=false")
      setLoading(false)
    }
  }

  fetchData()
}, [id, slug])
```

